<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1322,1743]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,542,1322,1347]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Taxonomic history and remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Draudt" box="[898,1058,1322,1346]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Draudt, M. (1919) Theclini F. In: A. Seitz (Ed). Die Gross-Schmetterlinge der Erde, vol. 5. Die amerikanischen Tagfalter, Alfred Kernen, Stuttgart, pp. 744 - 812." type="book chapter" year="1919">
Draudt (
<number box="[992,1050,1322,1346]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1919.0">1919</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
from a single male from Bogot√°. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lathy" box="[314,462,1358,1382]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Lathy, P. (1936) Thecla nouveaux d'Amerique du Sud (Lepidoptera Lycaenidae), In: Livre Jubilaire de M. Eugene-Louis Bouvier. Fermin-Didot et Cie., Paris, pp. 229 - 232." type="book chapter" year="1936">
Lathy (
<number box="[395,453,1358,1382]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1936.0">1936</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName box="[584,722,1358,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Thecla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliterata">
<emphasis box="[584,722,1358,1383]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">T. obliterata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a supposed male from Pampas, 
<collectingCountry box="[1148,1203,1359,1382]" name="Peru" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The specimen illustrated by Lathy is a female, not a male, and is now associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[907,1029,1395,1419]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dignota">
<emphasis box="[907,1029,1395,1419]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">M. dignota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clench" box="[1044,1205,1394,1418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Clench, H. K. (1971) Two new hairstreaks from Mexico (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae), Bulletin of the Allyn Museum, 3, 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1971">
Clench (
<number box="[1139,1197,1394,1418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1971.0">1971</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins" box="[1260,1436,1394,1418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Robbins, R. K. (2004) Checklist of Eumaeini. 98. Lycaenidae Theclinae, Eumaeini. 118 - 137 pp. In: Lamas, G., Checklist of Neotropical Lepidoptera. Part 4 A. Hesperioidea- Papilionoidea. Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera. J. Heppner (Ed.) Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, 439 pp." type="book chapter" year="2004">
Robbins (
<number box="[1369,1428,1394,1418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
correctly treated this species as a congener of 
<taxonomicName box="[665,898,1430,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platyptera">
<emphasis box="[665,898,1430,1454]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Micandra platyptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="61" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1322,1743]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1466,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males are easily distinguished by a rounded androconial brand in the distal portion of the discal cell. No other 
<taxonomicName box="[316,426,1502,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[316,426,1502,1526]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Micandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in 
<collectingCountry box="[557,667,1502,1526]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Colombia</collectingCountry>
has such a brand on the dorsal forewing. The rounded androconial brand is shared with 
<taxonomicName authority="Clench" authorityName="Clench" box="[383,611,1538,1563]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tongida">
<emphasis box="[383,506,1539,1563]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">M. tongida</emphasis>
(Clench)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[678,767,1538,1562]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Males and females are distinguished by the red-brown anal lobe on the dorsal hindwing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="61" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1322,1743]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1610,1635]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Distribution.</emphasis>
